<m0>Dorothy encounters in Oz is nearly as frightening as the wind that lifts her into the air.<ep>
   For the armchair traveler, the reward of watching mudslides in Missouri or blizzards in Chicago is a mix of voyeurism and smugness. On one hand, you get to ``experience'' the overwhelming power of Mother Nature from the comfort of your couch. On the other, you can pat yourself on the back for settling in Florida. That is, until the hurricanes or sinkholes arrive.<ep>
   As trends go, weather-calamity entertainment is part of a progression that began with adrenaline-pumping nature specials packed with footage of lions and crocodiles devouring cute furry creatures.<ep>
   In fact, these new documentaries reveal storm-chasing to be not just a fad but a cottage industry. (According to <m0>Savage Skies, <m0>people pay money to be put in the path of a twister. Go figure.) And, so far, the demand for these video weather products exceeds the supply (--) several of the documentaries contain the same Hurricane Andrew footage.<ep>
   With the way these films are proliferating, we can probably count on being entertained by real and fictional Midwesterners and Floridians battling the elements for years to come. <ep>
   For the producers, the best thing about this new genre is it's everywhere (--) and it's free. <m1> <m0>As one expert in <m0>Savage Skies <m0>puts it, weather ``comes right out of thin air.'' And there's new material arriving almost every day.<ql>
